	biburl = {https://dblp.org/rec/conf/trustcom/WangWZ23.bib},
	bibsource = {dblp computer science bibliography, https://dblp.org},
	abstract = {Network attack identification and analysis has been a difficult problem in cyberspace security research, and at present, the research on network attack identification based on deep learning models has achieved remarkable results. However, most of the models only use the temporal correlation of network traffic data to analyze, detect and warn the data, and do not make full use of the temporal correlation of the data, thus ignoring the topological information generated by the traffic in space. To address the above problems, this paper is attempt to use graph convolutional neural networks to solve the problem of network attack identification and analysis, and designs a deep learning model based on graph convolutional neural networks, which uses the correlation features between network flows to construct graph structure data, uses the spectral method in graph convolutional neural networks to transform the graph signal to the Fourier domain, and then performs convolutional operations in this domain, and through the learning of node features as well as topological information is learned to further enable the analysis and identification of known and unknown attacks. In this paper, we use the publicly available network traffic dataset UNSW-NB15_1, and the experimental results show that the detection accuracy of 9 types of network attacks is 99.43%; when "Analysis unknown attacks" are included in the test set, the detection accuracy of unknown attacks in it is 100%.}
