	bibsource = {dblp computer science bibliography, https://dblp.org},
	abstract = {It has been claimed that the biggest threat to an e-commerce provider’s ability to gain new customers has been the website’s general usability. The premises of equatricism presented in this research paper have shown that successful website participation is achieved through the owners reducing the amount of discomfort an actor will experience and maximizing the gratification the actor will experience. It is possible for a website to pass criteria for general usability, as with Google’s Gmail service, but for the personal usability criteria to not be met. Based on an autoethnographic approach, the authors of this research paper show how the use of ecological cognition and the participation continuum can explain behaviour change in e-commerce sites to assist in designing Internet environments.}
